{"key":"post-8553693","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8553693</id>\n<content>You don't grow mushrooms on a 'casing', you grow them on the substrate.&amp;nbsp; Any fruiting chamber you devise that will provide 95+ percent humidity and lots of air exchange will work great.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Cased substrates do NOT require a lower humidity and I always fail to know where people come up with such an idea.&amp;nbsp; Primordia form in near saturation humidity, provided there's plenty of fresh air.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Personally, I prefer a mini-greenhouse for cased substrates, but if you're only using one or two trays, you can use a shotgun or any other terrarium design that provides humidity and air exchange.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8554639</next>\n<prev>8553501</prev>\n<first>8553270</first>\n<last>8554745</last>\n<when>1214234841</when>\n<utime>06/23/08 06:27 PM</utime>\n</post>"}